--- UNIT-I SUMMARY ---

1. Abstract Data Type (ADT):
A mathematical model for data types where the data type is defined by its behavior (semantics) from the point of view of a user, of the data, specifically in terms of possible values, possible operations on data, and the behavior of these operations.

2. Singly Linked List (SLL):
- Linear collection of nodes, ordered by pointers.
- SLL Node Structure:
  struct node {
    int data;
    struct node *link;
  };
- Basic Operations:
  - Insert at Beginning: temp->link = head; head = temp;
  - Insert at End: Traversing to find the last node where link is NULL, then last->link = temp;
  - Insert at Position: Traversing to position-1 (prev), then temp->link = prev->link; prev->link = temp;
  - Delete Front: temp = head; head = head->link; delete temp;
  - Delete End: Traversing to find second-to-last node, then setting its link to NULL and freeing the last node.

3. Doubly Linked List (DLL):
- Nodes contain data and two self-referential pointers: prev and next.
- DLL Node Structure:
  struct node {
    int data;
    struct node *prev;
    struct node *next;
  };
- Permits bidirectional traversal.

4. Circular Linked List (CLL):
- The last node points back to the first node.
- No NULL pointer exists at the end of the list.
- Advantages:
  - Any node can be traversed starting from any other node.
  - Deletion is simplified as search for previous node can be started from that item itself.
